Let's now calculate the ordinary annuity payout. In this calculation, we will also consider the same provided detail of $2,500,000 cash flow, the 8% interest rate, and the period will be 35 years.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Ordinary annuity} &=\dfrac{.08\times \$2,500,000}{1-\left(1+.08\right)^{-35}}
\\[10pt]
&=\dfrac{\$200,000}{0.932365}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{\$214,508.26}
\end{aligned}$$

Hence, the payout if we use the ordinary annuity is $214,508.26

Let's calculate how much the difference we can withdraw should we use the ordinary annuity formula.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Net increase difference} &= \text{Amount of ordinary annuity }-\text{Amount of annuity due}
\\[5pt]
&=\$214,508.26-\$198,618.67
\\[5pt]
&= \boxed{\bf\$15,886.59}
\end{aligned}$$

**Therefore, if we consider the ordinary annuity calculation, we will have an increase in our withdrawal of $15,885.59.**
